-Title- 
How a TV Critic Manages a Franchise
-Keywords-
['star', 'franchise', 'fans', 'work', 'trek', 'critic', 'past', 'discovery', 'series', 'tv', 'good', 'course', 'manages']
-SUMMARY ARTICLE-
Of course, “Star Trek” isn’t just any story.
It would be malpractice for a TV critic not to know anything about “Star Trek.” I’d watched each of the series, more (“Deep Space Nine”) or less (sorry, “Enterprise”).
To an extent, my job is to know something about “Star Trek,” but simultaneously make myself forget it.
Some franchise fans have criticized the new series for breaking with the optimistic tone of past series.
The creators of a work like “Star Trek: Discovery” have to keep multiple audiences in mind.
-TEXT INSIDE ARTICLE-
This is great. But it’s not really my gig. As the chief television critic for a general-interest newspaper, as I’ve been for just over two years, my job is to be a grazer, a sampler, a dabbler. I don’t believe that there’s a hierarchy of fandom — that fans who have logged more eyeball-hours supporting a franchise are more authentic than other fans, and thus have greater ownership of the story.

So I write for the center of the “Star Trek” bell curve: the fan who may have seen a lot of the previous programs, or a little, or none at all, but who’s interested in “Discovery.” (This, by the way, is probably fine for the “Trek” superfan, who in today’s vast media cosmos can find plenty of more-targeted reviews from the standpoint of completists.)

Of course, “Star Trek” isn’t just any story. It’s part of our national mythology, a continuing megastory whose characters come to represent our abstract ideals. It would be malpractice for a TV critic not to know anything about “Star Trek.” I’d watched each of the series, more (“Deep Space Nine”) or less (sorry, “Enterprise”).

This kind of question — how much does the source material matter? — comes up more often as pop culture has become dominated by adaptations (“Game of Thrones”), revivals (“The X-Files”), reboots (“Dynasty”), sequels (“Fuller House”), prequels (“Young Sheldon”) and remakes of adaptations (“The Tick”).

It’s as if we were trapped in a time loop reliving the past … not unlike the “Star Trek: The Next Generation” crew in the episode “Cause and Effect.”

My philosophy is that any work needs to stand on its own: If I need to have read the source book to really “get” a TV series, then it’s not a good series. It’s not an iron rule, of course. Good luck understanding “Twin Peaks: The Return” if you didn’t see the original. (Then again, good luck even if you did see the original.)

Likewise, part of what I need to ask about a show like “Discovery” is: If it weren’t associated with this brand, would I want to watch any more of it? To an extent, my job is to know something about “Star Trek,” but simultaneously make myself forget it.

I address some of these meta-questions in my review of “Discovery,” which I wrote after watching six episodes. Some franchise fans have criticized the new series for breaking with the optimistic tone of past series. I don’t have that problem, although I had other issues. Franchises stay vital by remaking themselves for their times, not by pledging allegiance to the past. Just as Batman could be a camp icon in the 1960s and a brooding antihero in the 21st century, so can “Trek” complicate itself for the era of complex TV.

Advertisement Continue reading the main story

Of course, it’s not just critics who have to think about this. The creators of a work like “Star Trek: Discovery” have to keep multiple audiences in mind. After all, CBS was probably counting on the passionate “Trek” fan base to drive subscriptions to its All Access streaming service.

But a franchise also needs new fans to grow. If you become too beholden to callbacks and timelines, you risk becoming less a storyteller and more of a custodian. It’s a big universe, and “Star Trek” belongs to all of it.
--------------------------------------------------------------

-Title- 
An Auction Setup at Christie’s: First a Marathon, Then a Sprint
-Keywords-
['art', 'sarokin', 'ms', 'client', 'gallery', 'setup', 'york', 'sprint', 'billion', 'marathon', 'involved', 'auction', 'christies']
-SUMMARY ARTICLE-
Emily Sarokin may not have completely understood how a major auction house worked when she joined Christie’s New York six years ago.
“I had no idea.”She knows now that it is “an immense machine.” In 2016, there were 84 sales and more than 100 exhibitions at Christie’s New York location alone.
They involved art and other precious goods worth about 1.5 billion pounds.
Ms. Sarokin, 29, described working intensely and constantly with shippers, contractors, riggers, lawyers and (of course) the art handlers.
Advertisement Continue reading the main storyA thousand decisions, visions and revisions are involved: What humidity level does this piece require?
-TEXT INSIDE ARTICLE-
Emily Sarokin may not have completely understood how a major auction house worked when she joined Christie’s New York six years ago.

“I thought it was ‘Antiques Roadshow,’” Ms. Sarokin, the vice president and director of gallery operations and client services, said in a recent interview at the Rockefeller Center gallery, laughing at herself as she prepared for the Fine Chinese Ceramics and Works of Art auction in mid-September. “I had no idea.”

She knows now that it is “an immense machine.” In 2016, there were 84 sales and more than 100 exhibitions at Christie’s New York location alone. They involved art and other precious goods worth about 1.5 billion pounds. That is almost $2 billion (but employees tend to think in British currency because the head office is in London, where the company was founded in 1766).

The number of details involved in creating any one of those events in 57,000 square feet of Midtown exhibition space is complicated. Ms. Sarokin, 29, described working intensely and constantly with shippers, contractors, riggers, lawyers and (of course) the art handlers.

Advertisement Continue reading the main story

A thousand decisions, visions and revisions are involved: What humidity level does this piece require? How long will that shipment take to get through customs in Hong Kong? What do we do when a client calls and says, “I’m in town, I have 30 minutes before lunch, and I want to see this $30 million painting”?
