And Finally ...

In the charred rubble of Santa Rosa it was the McDonald’s that drew Penny Wolin, a photographer who lives nearby.

Touring the destruction last week, she said she was stunned by the amount of destruction. “I had to really calm down,” she said.

She arrived at a shopping complex on the western edge of the 101 Freeway, which the Tubbs Fire had leapt in its sprint into the Coffey Park neighborhood.

A Kmart and an Americas Best Value Inn had been incinerated. So had the McDonald’s, yet some of the restaurant’s cheery exterior remained intact.

“It’s still looking sort of normal, like ‘Come on in,’” said Ms. Wolin, 64. “But in fact the plastic is melted on the post and the arches had fallen to the ground and the ‘McDonald’s’ is so burned it’s almost a black-and-white photograph.”

She continued, “I’ll tell you, that, for me, tells the whole thing and points the way to our larger American society for the moment.”

Ms. Wolin shared a collection of her images. It’s called “Good Morning McDonald’s.”
