-Title- 
Review: In ‘Lonely Planet,’ Mismatched Friends and an Unnamed Plague
-Keywords-
['plague', 'sign', 'mismatched', 'jodys', 'carl', 'way', 'lonely', 'york', 'review', 'chairs', 'mr', 'planet', 'makes', 'jody', 'times', 'unnamed', 'friends']
-SUMMARY ARTICLE-
PhotoThe first sign of unsettlement is when Carl starts bringing mismatched chairs to Jody’s shop, where the play takes place, claiming his own apartment is too small.
This is par for the course in “Lonely Planet,” which makes liberal use of symbols and metaphors, yet manages to be heavy-handed while not spelling things out.
View all New York Times newsletters.
But under his flip exterior — and Mr. McGrath makes hay of Carl’s wit — the show’s resident jester is angry at the disease that is killing his friends.
At least Carl confronts the plague in his own way, and he is getting frustrated and scared by Jody’s denial of reality.
-TEXT INSIDE ARTICLE-
But Mr. Dietz has something besides humor in mind (even if there is plenty of it) and that something — the weight of grief, the paralyzing fear of illness — emerges over the course of the show, like a photograph coming into focus in a dark room.

Photo

The first sign of unsettlement is when Carl starts bringing mismatched chairs to Jody’s shop, where the play takes place, claiming his own apartment is too small. As the chairs progressively take over the space, we learn that Jody has stopped going home. He hasn’t been tested, he tells Carl, and does not want to leave the comfort of his familiar, mapped-out little universe anymore.

Mr. Dietz never says what Jody has not been tested for, but the two protagonists are gay men in the early 1990s, and conclusions are easy to draw that it is AIDS. This is par for the course in “Lonely Planet,” which makes liberal use of symbols and metaphors, yet manages to be heavy-handed while not spelling things out.

Most obviously, Jody uses cartography to evoke the way he sees the world, as when he talks about the flat Mercator map — which misrepresents the size of countries, with those farther away from the Equator appearing larger — and makes us accept “the distortion as fact.”

Newsletter Sign Up Continue reading the main story Please verify you're not a robot by clicking the box. Invalid email address. Please re-enter. You must select a newsletter to subscribe to. Sign Up You agree to receive occasional updates and special offers for The New York Times's products and services. Thank you for subscribing. An error has occurred. Please try again later. View all New York Times newsletters.

Jody is also seen reading Ionesco’s absurdist, despairing, agonizingly elliptical play “The Chairs.” “Is it the one with the hippos?” Carl quips. But under his flip exterior — and Mr. McGrath makes hay of Carl’s wit — the show’s resident jester is angry at the disease that is killing his friends.

The chairs he is amassing in Jody’s store belonged to people who just died; they are totems of snuffed-out lives. At least Carl confronts the plague in his own way, and he is getting frustrated and scared by Jody’s denial of reality.

In the plain, affectless staging by Jonathan Silverstein, Mr. Burton and Mr. McGrath expertly underplay the characters, with their roiling fears and, in Carl’s case, outrage. You may wish, at times, for a dash of immoderation, but the show’s deceptively gentle approach is also what makes it stand apart in our angry times.
